{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280602024/1937092101/0024.xml":{"full_text":"OPTIMISM MARKS\nCHAMBER REVIEW\n\nBusiness Is Ready to Move\nForward During Fall,\nReport States.\nBV EDWARD C. STONE.\nThe United States Chamber of\nCommerce is \u2018'bullish\u201d on the Fall\nbusiness outlook, this week's review\nstating that production and distribu\ntion, employment and pay rolls, came\nthrough the Summer with their\nearlier gains intact. The survey adds:\n\u201cOn the face of the record the\nbusiness of the country at large is\nobviously ready to go forward during\nthe Fall months of 1937 as during the\nFall months of 1936, with steadily in\ncreasing production for the country as\na whole keeping pace with an ex\npanding consumption and a growing\n\"xport trade and with additions to\nemployment to the point of labor\nshortage.\n\u201cWholesale price levels have main\ntained stability that would be impos\nsible in the absence of healthy condi\ntions; the index of wholesale food\nprices in early September is almost\nidentical with the index of September\n1935: the index for wholesale prices\nof all farm products is up 6 per cent\nfrom the figure of two years before;\nsnd in the same period the general\nlevels of wholesale prices for finished\nmanufactured products has risen by\nalmost the same percentage as the\ngeneral level of prices for farm prod\nucts.\n\u201cThe average cost of living has been\nno less favorable. In the two years\nsince September 1935, it has risen by\nonly 6 per cent, and according to the\nLabor Department, less than 2 per cent\nduring the last year. On the other\nhand,*average weekly earnings of all\nworkers in industry have risen 23 per\ncent.\n\u201cUse of bank credit reflects much\nPreparation for business in the im\nm/'Hintja fllElirn u a.\nweeks of September commercial, in\ndustrial and agricultural loans by\nfederal Reserve member banks in 101\n\"ities rose by $82,000,000, or sub\nJantially more than during the same\nperiod last year.\"\nNew Chairman to Preside.\nMyrtle P. Lewis, this year\u2019s chair\nman of the Women\u2019s Committee, Amer\ncan Institute of Banking, who will\n\u2019\u2019reside at the committee's dinner\nomorrow evening at the Mayflower\nHotel, was secretary of Washington\nChapter last year and has served on\nnany important\nommittees. She\ns connected with\nhe Liberty Ma\nin n a 1 Bank.\nOther members\nif the Women\u2019s\nCommittee i n\n'lude:\nMarguerite\nTetterer, Ameri\ncan Security\nrrust Co.: Alice\nH. Whitton. First\nnational Bank,\nMexandria: Viv- l\nan Stokes and\nMyrtle P. Lewis.\nMargaret A. Fis\nher, Hamilton National; Gertrude C.\nWick, Liberty National; Ann Crawford,\nMrLachlen Banking Corp.; Sadye L.\nWeir and Margaret Berckmann, Na\nional Metropolitan; Constance Jones.\nMildred ODonoghue and Harriet\n3arr<;tt, Riggs National: Etheline Par\ncel-. Security Savings Commercial\nHank; Naomi DeLozier, Second Na\nional; Janet Gibbons, Union Trust\nCo Katherine McCalmont, W. B.\nHibbs Co.; Leona Draeger and Rose\nRoyce. Washington Loan Trust Co.\nBond Pamphlet Distributed.\nLazard Freres Co. have issued a\nrevised edition of their pamphlet,\nCallable Bond Issues, listing 300\nallable railroad, public utility and\nndustrial bonds carrying coupons up\nvard of 4 per cent, which have sold\nit or near their call prices this year.\n\u2019t contains data designed to provide\nKind buyers with a basis for determin\nng at what price purchase: of such\nionds is desirable.\nAgency Notes 92nd Anniversary.\nWith a banquet at the Chevy Chase\nClub last night, the 92nd anniversary\nif the founding of the Washington\nigency of the Mutual Benefit Life\ninsurance Co. of New Jersey was ob\nserved by the whole agency staff.\nHerbert G. Kenagy, superintendent of\nagencies, and William H. Gaither, field\n-ervice manager! spoke, congratulating\nthe agents on the success of the past\nyear, especially in the service work\nrendered policy holders. Others pres\nent included:\nEdward P. Parker, James A. de\nForce, Croom Walker, Charles M.\nSchwab. Francis Miller, Theodore E.\nGero, V. Louise Bergmann, Roscoe\nApplegate, Dwight T. Scott, Joseph W.\noiDson, frame D. Roach, George C.\nCampbell, Adolph Krechel, *George T,\nHoward and H. Lawrence Choate, gen\neral agent.\nThe Mutual Benefit is the oldest\nlife insurance office in the city, having\nbeen started by Joseph C. Lewis in\nSeptember, 1845,\nAbout 250 in Rank School.\nWashington Chapter, American In\nstitute of Banking, opened the school\nyear last night with an enrollment of\nabout 250 junior bankers. During the\npast two weeks enrollments have been\nreceived at headquarters in the Bond\nBuilding and the results are very grati\nfying to chapter officials. The courses\nplanned for the year have been ex\npanded and will be unusually helpful\nto all bank employes. Employes in the\nTreasury are now allowed to take in\nstitute courses in Washington chapter.\nSeveral will again avail themselves of\nthis opportunity during the present\nyear. Paul J. Seltzer. American Se\ncurity Trust Co., is chairman of the\nEducational Committee.\nHeard in Financial District.\nMarshall O. Exnicios, vice president\nof Robert C. Jones Co., Inc., invest\nment bankers, has been on an exten\nsive vacation in Europe since July. He\nIs scheduled to return to his office\nabout the 1st of October.\nWillard G. Barker, president of the\nMorris Plan Bank, has returned from\nColorado Springs, where he attended\nthe annual convention of the Morris\nPlan Bank Association. He reports a\nmost interesting series of meetings.\nIt is announced that the Atlantic\nStates Shippers' Advisory Board will\nhold its forty-fourth regular meeting\nat Newark, N. J., on October 6 and J.\nToday\u2019s Trading on Exchange.\nWashington Gas Light new prefer\nred stock again drew all the atten\ntion on the Washington Stock Ex\nchange today. The market opened\n\u2022with several sales at 98 Vi. After call\nsix or seven small-lot transactions\nwere recorded at 98.\nBid and asked prices on other stocks\nand bonds recorded very few changes.\nTRANSACTIONS ON THE NEW YORK STOCK EXCHANGE\nBj Private Wire Direct to The Star.\nPrev 1937 Stock and Bales\u2014 Net\nHleli. Low. Dividend Rate. Add 00. Rich. Low. Close, chgs.\n85 63% Acme Steel (4)_ 2 68 67 68 +2\n22% 14% Adams Exp <.30g)_. 16 14% 14% 14%+%\n36 26% Addressog <1.40)_ 1 27% 27% 27%\n80% 61% Air Reduction (la). 8 64% 64 64 -1%\n6% 1% Air-Way El Ap_ 1 1% 1% 1%\n15% 9% Alaska Jun <.60a)__ 7 10% 10V> 10%-%\n5% 1% Alleghany- 26 2 1% 1%\n59% 18 Allec pf {30 ww_ 5 19% 19 19V* +1%\n62% 19 Allegprpf- 7 20% 19% 19%+\n46% 25 Altek Steel (1.20g)_ 8 28% 27 27 +1%\n27% 13 Allen Indus (1)- 6 14% 14 14%\n258% 183 Allied Chem <6)_ 8 192% 188 188 +2\n17% 14% Allied Kid (la)_ 1 14% 14% 14% Vi\n33% 17% Allied Mills <2g)___ 7 18 IV,k 18\n21% 13% Allied Stores <.20a). 26 13% 13% 13%\n83% 53% Allis Chaim (2g)__. 16 57 64 64% ii\n8% 3% Amal Leath__ 1 4 4 4\n114% 71% Amerada (2)_ 5 74 72 72 \u20141\n41% 20 Am Bank Note %g_ 13 21% 20 20\n80% 45 Am Brake Sh (2g).. 4 49% 49 49\n121 90% Am Can (4a)- 10 96% 95% 96% +1%\n71 29 Am Car Fy (%g). 10 32% 31% 31%\n104% 61 Am Car F pf (4g). 1 60 60 60 \u20141\n33% 24 Am Ch&Cable lg.__ 16 26% 25% 25%-%\nL12 98 Am Chicle (4a)_ 6 100% 99% 100%\n23% 10 Am Colortype_ 3 12 11% 12\n30% 17% Am Cornel Alco_' 4 20 19% 19%+\n33% 20% Am Crys Sug 3.25g. 2 21% 21 21%+%\n13% 5% Am Encaustic Til _ 8 6 5% 5%\n13% 4% Am Foreign Pow. 22 5% 6% 6%\n58% 25 Am F P $6 pf_ 5 27% 27 27 -1%\n68% 34 Am For Pw $7 pf. 14 36% 35% 36% +2%\n38% 13% Am For Pw 2d pf. 10 15 14% 14%\n11V* 6 Am Hide Leath 6 6% 6% 5%\n52% 39% Am Home Pr (2.40). 6 40% 39% 39%\n4% 2% Am Ice 6 2% 2% 2%\n27% 17% Am lee pf (1.50g)_ 1 22 22 22 +1\n17% 10% Am International_ 6 10% 10% 10%\n58% 28% Am Locomotive_ 11 31% 30 30% V,\nL25 90 Am Loco pf- 2 90% 90 90\n29% 16% Am M Fdy <%g)_ 6 17% 17 17 Vi\n68% 39% Am Metal (%g) 10 42 41% 41% +1\n75 60 Am News N Y (3).. 60a 62 61% 62\n16% 7 Am Pow Lt_ 17 