stock, g Declared or paid so far this\nyear. h Cash or stock, k Accumulated dividend paid or de- j\ndared this year.\n\nArmco Discloses\nNew High Mark in\nSheet Shipments\nBv the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, September 21.\u2014\nAmerican Rolling Mill Co., exclusive\nof its subsidiaries, set a new high mark\nin shipments of iron and steel sheets\nin the first eight months of this year.\nShipments were 14 per cent ahead\nof the same period last year and 48\nper cent over the like months of 1929,\nthe company announced.\nNEW FIRM FORMED.\nPHILADELPHIA, September 21\n(Special).\u2014Announcement is being\nmade today by Henry P. Carr and\nJoseph L. O\u2019Brien of the formation\nof Carr-O\u2019Brien Co., and the opening\nof offices in the Packard Building.\nThe new firm will carry on a business\nin general investment securities.\nR.-M. T. MEETING DELAYED.\nNEW YORK, September 21\nThe annual stockholders\u2019 meeting' of\nthe Brooklyn-Manhattan Transit Co.,\nscheduled for today, was postponed two\nweeks due to lack of a quoroum.\nNEW YORK COTTON\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. September 21.\u2014Cot\nton moved narrowly today and the\nundertone held steady on trade sup\nport. Hedge selling let up somewhat.\nFirmness of the stock market failed\nto attract aggressive buying but\nseemed to counterbalance favorable\nweather in the South.\nDecember sold up from 8.63 to 8.67\nand in midafternoon traded at 8.65.\nPrices were 1 to 3 cents net higher.\nPiltur\u00ab closed barely steady, unheanged\nto 2 lower.\nHigh. Low. Last.\nOctober \u20142._ 8.80 8.7:! 8.7 2\nDecember _ 8.67 8.61 8.61-62\nJanuary___ 8.72 8.67 8.67-68\nMarch _ 8.81 8.75 8.75\nMay _ __ 8.92 8.86 8.86-87\nJuly __ 9.02 8.80 8.96-97\nSpot quiet; middling. 8.99.\nCottonseed Oil.\nBleachable cottonseed oil futures\nclosed steady, 1 to 3 lower. Sales, 150\ncontracts. October, 7.23-24; Decem\nber, 7.28-29; January, 7.31-33; March,\n7.36b; May, 7.42-43. b\u2014Bid.N\nNew Orleans Prices.\nNEW ORLEANS, September 21 UP.\u2014\nTrading was ouiet in the cotton market\nhere early today and first transactions\nwere 1 point net higher to 1 point lower.\nPressure was lacking from either side\nand there was little desire t.o enter upon\nnew commitments pending some stimu\nlating Influence. Foreign markets were\nsteady and early weather advices favor\nable.\nOctober opened at 8.89 bid, b\u00abt reeov\nered to 8.72 soon after thp start. De\ncember opened at 8.70. January 8 14.\nMarch 8.84 and July P.04. A few buy\ning orders weie executed in *he first half\nhour and prices rallied to levels 1 to\npoints above the previous close\nReporter from Worth street said a fair\ninquiry continued in textiles. Liverpool\ncables were better than due and Egyptian\nfutures were higher.\nCottonseed oil opened steady: Seprem-\nher. (5.78b: October. (5.72b December. 1\n(5.75b: January, 0.77b, March, 6.8.\u20185b.\nb\u2014Bid.\n\nAUTOMOTIVE EXPORTS\nUP SHARPLY IN JULY\nB> the Associated Press.\nThe Bureau of Foreign and Do\nmestic Commerce reported yesterday\nexports of automotive pr \u2019ucts from\nthe Un'\u2018ed States in July were valued\nat 73 per cent more than exports in\nJuly, 1936.\nLast July's exports totaled $30,669,\n383, compared with $17,754,406 in the\nsame month of 1936. This country ex\nported 19,115 passenger cars valued\nat $10,531,006 last July, compared with\n12,531 cars valued at $6,576,588 in the\ncorresponding month of 1936.\nThere were 15,114 trucks valued at\n$9,505,175 exported in July this year,\ncompared with 9.725 valued at $4,\n947,973 In July, 1936.\n0\nBaltimore Ohio R. R.\u2014Deficit\nseven months ended July 31, was\n$353,477, against deficit of $1,820,819.\nAFTERJARLY RISE\nClimb $1 to $3 Before Late\nSelling Wipes Out Part\nof Advance.\nStock Averages\nno is is \u00abn\nIndust. Rails. Uv! Stocks\nNet change.t-1.2-r-10 -*-.5 9\nToday noo^t. 82.2 30 6 37 9 58 0\nPrevious day 81.0 29.6 37.4 57.1\nMonth ago\u2014 96 0 37.6 41.8 67 6\nYear ago_ 90.9 41.1 51.8 68.6\n1937 high\u2014.101.6 49 5 54 0 75.3\n1937 low_ 81.0 29.2 37.4 57.1\n1936 high\u2014 99.3 43.5 53.7 72.8\n1936 low_ 73.4 30.2 43.4 55.7\n1932 low 17.5 8.7 23.9 16.9\n1929 high\u2014 146.9 153.9 184 3 157.7\n1927 low... 51.6 95.3 61.8 61.8\n(Complied by the Associated Preee.)\nBY VICTOR EUBANK,\nAssociated Press Financial Writer.\nNEW YORK, September 21.\u2014Stocks\ncrawled into a recovery move for 1\nto 3 or more points in today's early*\nmarket dealings but a late selling push\nunsettled leaders at the finish.\nRails held the play from the start,\nwith most other groups taking part\nLack of volume, however, dampened\nbuying courage in the final hour and\ntraders were quick to take profits\nLightness of dealings was said to\nhave been caused partially by absence\nof numerous board room customers\nwho were either participating or wit\nnessing the huge American Legion\nparade.\nStrength of American issues in\nAmsterdam and London, after their\nrecent relapse, apparently helped buoy\nsentiment at the opening Improve.,\nmrnt in bonds and commodities, on\nthe whole, was also encouraging.\nOutstanding news from a market\nstandpoint was scarce and broKrrs\nthought much of the morning rally\nwas due to belief the list had been\noversold in the past several weeks\nTransfers were around 1,000.000\nshares.\nCarriers attracted friends on re\nports from Chit ago that the wage con\ntroversy, after lengthy negotiations,\nwas nearer settlement than generally\nsupposed.\nStocks on top most of the time in\ncluded U. S. Steel. Crucible. Acme\nSteel, Superior *Steel, N. Y. Central,\nPennsylvania, Southern Pacific. South\nern Railway, Great Northern, Balti\nmore Ohio, Union Pacific, Pullman,\nU. S. Rubber. Chrysler, General Mot\nors. Montgomery Ward. J. I. Case,\nOliver Farm. Anaetr.ria. Kennecott,\nAmerican Smelting, Detroit Edison.\nBoeing. St. Joseph Lead. American\nMetal, Philip Morns, American Can.\nGeneral Electric, Du Pont, Allied\nChemical. Johns-Manville. Paramount,\nEastman Kodak and International\nPaper Power preferred (new;.\nInclined to give ground were Cerro\nde Pasco. Dpere, Caterpillar Tractor.\nUnion Carbide, Loews and Allis\nChalmers.\nCopper Futures\nEdge Higher as\nMarket Steadies\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEVv\u2019 YORK. September 21.\u2014Cop\nper prices steadied and futures edged\nup a little today after yesterday's sharp\nbreak.\nExport copper sold at slightly under\n13 cents a pound, or a cent less than\nthe 14-cent domestic price for the\nmetal for immediate delivery, which\nhas been maintained for some time\nFutures rose 1-6 to 1-10 of a cent, but\ncontracts continued below 12 cents, nr\n2 cents under the domestic spot price.\nIn normal markets, when the gap\nbetween the export and domestic spat\nprice widens to a half cent or more\ntraders anticipate a change to the do\nmestic price.\nCHICAGO GRAIN\nBy the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO. September 21\u2014Strained\nconditions in September rorn dealing.'\nwere intensified today by further lively\njumps of prices, though new top quo\ntations were not fully maintained.\nFederal authorities look official cog\nnizance of unusual stubbomess both\nof bulls and bears, and served virtual\nnotice that strict requirements in re\ngard to the market position of all\ntraders in September rorn would be\nenforced to the utmost. Announce\nments posted indicated nevertheless\nthat only 98.000 bushels of corn would\nbe delivered tomorrow on Septemocr\ncontracts.\nAt the close the corn market as a\nwhole was 3a-2% cents above yester\nday's finish. September. 104%-%: De\ncember. 64%-V wheat, %-l rent up,\nSeptember 1.05sa-a4. December,\n1 0534-l 06. and oats unchanged to\nadvanced.\nwheat\u2014\nOpen. Hieh. Low. Close\nSop\u2014 1.04% 1 t is 1m4% 105V'.,\nDoc 1.04 108', .04% 1 0.V*4-08\nMay 1.08% 1.08% 1.08% 1.07%-%\nCORN\u2014\nSop. 1.02% 1.05% 102% 104%-%\nDot _ .70% .72% .70% ,7|%\nDoc. .83 .85% .83% .84%-%\nMay 84% .85% .84% .84%-%\nOATS\nSop. .32% .32% .32 .32%\nDoc. .30% .31% .30% .31-31%\nMay